    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "62563a3fccb6eb7e",
      "text": "With two connections, only very trivial networks can ever be made. But if one uses three connections, a vast range of networks immediately become possible. One might think that one could get a fundamentally larger range if one allowed, say, four or five connections rather than just three. But in fact one cannot, since any node with more than three connections can in effect always be broken into a collection of nodes with exactly three connections, […]."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8ea4e0e92757543b",
      "text": "So what this means is that it is in a sense always sufficient to consider networks with exactly three connections at each node. And it is therefore these networks that [[Stephen Wolfram]] will use here in discussing fundamental models of space.\n"
    },
